rdf:Description.rdfs:label: symmetric
rdf:Description.obo:IAO_0000115: Symmetric slot

Used to extend an existing class definition. For example, if we have a core schema where a gene has two slots for identifier and symbol, and we have a specialized schema for my_organism where we wish to add a slot systematic_name, we can avoid subclassing by defining a class gene_my_organism, adding the slot to this class, and then adding an apply_to pointing to the gene class. The new slot will be 'injected into' the gene class.
rdf:Description.rdfs:label: apply_to

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: alias

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: slot_usage
rdf:Description.obo:IAO_0000115: Additional info on how a slot is used in the context of a class. Many slots may be re-used across different classes, but the meaning of the slot may be refined by context. For example, a generic association model may use slots subject/predicate/object with generic semantics and minimal constraints. When this is subclasses, e.g. to disease-phenotype associations then slot_usage may specify both local naming (e.g. subject=disease) and local constraints

rdf:Description.rdfs:label: slot definition is_a
rdf:Description.obo:IAO_0000115: specifies single-inheritance between classes and slots. While multiple inheritance is not allowed, mixins can be provided effectively providing the same thing. The semantics are the same when translated to formalisms that allow MI (e.g. RDFS/OWL). When translating to a SI framework (e.g. java classes, python classes) then is_a is used. When translating a framework without polymorphism (e.g. json-schema, solr document schema) then is_a and mixins are recursively unfolded
